m Plato to Kant and Emerson, the book features chapters on each of Melville, Thoreau, Pound, Moore, O'Hara, and Schuyler. Each chapter presents an aspect of the writer as enthusiast, the book as a whole charting the changing sense of literary enthusiasm from Romanticism to the present day. Lucidly written and combatively argued, the book will appeal to readers of American Literature or Modern Poetry, and to all those interested in the circulation of literary work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEnthusiasm in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aEzra Pound.  aFrank O'Hara.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aImmanuel Kant.  aJames Schuyle.  aMarianne Moore.  aRalph Waldo Emerson.  aSocrates.  aWilliam Penn.  acultural activism.  aenthusiasm.  anearer testament.  apolemic.  atransmission of literature.  aunbridled self.1 aHerd, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526125118zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125118zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125118/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA